  <h2 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-white mb-4">Why the "7x Rule" Is Wrong</h2>
  <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-[#888] leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      The idea that one dog year equals seven human years likely originated in the 1950s as a simple marketing slogan. While the "multiply by 7" method is easy to remember, it's scientifically flawed for several reasons:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">It ignores breed size.</strong> A Great Dane and a Chihuahua age at very different rates. The 7x rule treats all dogs identically, which couldn't be further from the truth.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">Aging isn't linear.</strong> Dogs age much faster in their first two years than later in life. A 1-year-old dog isn't 7 in human years — they're about 31 based on DNA methylation research.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">It misleads health decisions.</strong> Using the 7x rule, a 10-year-old dog would be 70 — potentially leading owners to miss the transition to senior care at the right time for their specific breed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">No scientific basis.</strong> The 7x rule has never been validated by any scientific study. Modern methods use DNA methylation — biological markers that actually measure aging at the cellular level.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[#666] pt-2">
      <strong class="text-white">The bottom line:</strong> Use a breed-size adjusted calculator like ours for accurate results. Your dog deserves better than a 1950s marketing gimmick.
    </p>
